Java follows the same principles: case‑sensitive methods, `Objects.equals()` before `==` (unless primitives), and `array.length`.

---

## 5. Take‑aways & best practices

| Practice | Why it matters |
|----------|----------------|
| **Prefer descriptive names** (`target`, `cultureArray`, `resetService`) | Self‑documenting code is easier to maintain. |
| **Use proper API casing** | Avoid compile‑time errors and typos. |
| **Avoid repeated “else” logging** | Reduces noise and potential I/O bottlenecks. |
| **Break out after success** | Performance improvement & logical clarity. |
| **Wrap side‑effect calls in try/catch** | Prevents unhandled exceptions from crashing the loop. |
| **Unit‑test the snippet** | Verify edge cases: empty array, multiple matches, null entries, etc. |

